  <h2>Why Ammonia Control Is Critical</h2>
  <p>
    Ammonia is the silent killer in shrimp ponds. Even at low concentrations, it damages gills, suppresses immune function, and makes shrimp vulnerable to disease. At high levels, it causes mass mortality within hours. Understanding and controlling ammonia is perhaps the most important skill for any shrimp farmer.
  </p>

  <h2>Understanding Ammonia in Aquaculture</h2>

  <h3>What Is Ammonia?</h3>
  <p>
    Ammonia (NH₃/NH₄⁺) is a nitrogenous waste product excreted by shrimp through their gills and produced by the decomposition of uneaten feed and organic matter. It exists in two forms in water:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Un-ionized ammonia (NH₃):</strong> The toxic form — harmful at concentrations above 0.02 mg/L</li>
    <li><strong>Ionized ammonia (NH₄⁺):</strong> Less toxic, but still contributes to total ammonia nitrogen (TAN)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>When Is Ammonia Most Dangerous?</h3>
  <p>
    Ammonia toxicity increases with:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Higher pH:</strong> At pH 9.0, un-ionized ammonia is 10x more toxic than at pH 7.0</li>
    <li><strong>Higher temperature:</strong> Warm water increases the proportion of toxic un-ionized ammonia</li>
    <li><strong>Low dissolved oxygen:</strong> Stressed shrimp are more susceptible to ammonia damage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sources of Ammonia in Ponds</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Shrimp excretion:</strong> Primary source — shrimp excrete ammonia continuously</li>
    <li><strong>Uneaten feed:</strong> Decomposes and releases ammonia</li>
    <li><strong>Fecal matter:</strong> Breaks down into ammonia through bacterial action</li>
    <li><strong>Organic sludge:</strong> Accumulated bottom waste releases ammonia over time</li>
    <li><strong>Fertilizers:</strong> Some nitrogen-based fertilizers contribute to ammonia levels</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Monitoring Ammonia Levels</h2>

  <h3>Testing Schedule</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>First 2 weeks after stocking:</strong> Test daily (critical period)</li>
    <li><strong>During grow-out:</strong> Test every 2-3 days</li>
    <li><strong>Before and after feeding:</strong> Test to understand patterns</li>
    <li><strong>After rain or water changes:</strong> Test immediately</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Safe Levels</h3>
  <p>
    For optimal shrimp health:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Total Ammonia Nitrogen (TAN):</strong> Below 0.5 ppm</li>
    <li><strong>Un-ionized ammonia (NH₃):</strong> Below 0.02 ppm</li>
    <li><strong>Critical threshold:</strong> Above 1.0 ppm TAN causes stress; above 2.0 ppm causes mortality</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Practical Ammonia Control Strategies</h2>

  <h3>1. Water Quality Management</h3>
  <p>
    The most effective long-term strategy is maintaining a healthy biological filter. Nitrifying bacteria convert ammonia to nitrite and then to harmless nitrate. Support these bacteria with:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Regular water exchanges (10-20% weekly)</li>
    <li>Maintaining alkalinity above 150 mg/L</li>
    <li>Ensuring dissolved oxygen above 4 mg/L</li>
    <li>Avoiding overuse of antibiotics that kill beneficial bacteria</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2. Feed Management</h3>
  <p>
    Overfeeding is the #1 cause of ammonia spikes. Follow these guidelines:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Feed 3-4 times daily at 3-5% of body weight</li>
    <li>Use feeding trays to monitor consumption</li>
    <li>Remove uneaten feed after 30 minutes</li>
    <li>Use feed enzyme supplements to improve digestion and reduce waste</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3. Probiotic Application</h3>
  <p>
    Beneficial bacteria like those in AquaBio Pro compete with pathogenic bacteria and help break down organic waste before it converts to ammonia. Apply regularly:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Feed application: daily with feed</li>
    <li>Water application: every 2 weeks at 1 kg/ha</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>4. Emergency Ammonia Treatment</h3>
  <p>
    When ammonia spikes above safe levels, act immediately:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Increase aeration to maximum</li>
    <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Apply AmmoniClear Pro to bind ammonia instantly</li>
    <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Perform 20-30% water change</li>
    <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Reduce feeding by 50% for 2-3 days</li>
    <li><strong>Step 5:</strong> Test again in 6 hours</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>5. Bottom Soil Management</h3>
  <p>
    Accumulated organic sludge on pond bottoms continuously releases ammonia. Prevent this by:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Applying Soil Renew during pond preparation</li>
    <li>Maintaining proper aeration to keep solids suspended</li>
    <li>Using sediment traps or siphoning to remove excess solids</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Building Ammonia-Resilient Ponds</h2>
  <p>
    The goal is not just to react to ammonia spikes but to build ponds that resist them. This means:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Proper pond preparation before stocking</li>
    <li>Healthy biological filtration from day one</li>
    <li>Consistent water quality monitoring</li>
    <li>Balanced feeding practices</li>
    <li>Regular probiotic application</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    With these practices in place, ammonia control becomes manageable rather than crisis-driven.
  </p>

